Every C++ program starts with `int main()`. Output uses `std::cout` and input uses `std::cin`, both from `#include <iostream>`.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
int main() {
    std::cout << "Hello, World!\n";
    return 0;
}
```

- `std::` â€” the standard namespace prefix
- `<<` â€” insertion operator (sends data to `cout`)
- `>>` â€” extraction operator (reads data from `cin`)
- `return 0;` â€” signals successful execution
- `//` â€” single-line comment
- `/* ... */` â€” multi-line comment

**`std::format` (C++20)** â€” type-safe, Pythonic formatting:
```cpp
#include <format>
std::cout << std::format("Hello, {}! Age: {}\n", name, age);
```

**`std::print` (C++23)** â€” even simpler: `std::print("val={}", x);`

**Stream buffers (`std::streambuf`)** â€” the underlying mechanism behind all streams. You can redirect `std::cout` to a file by swapping its buffer.

**`std::ios::sync_with_stdio(false)`** â€” disables C/C++ stream synchronization for faster I/O (common in competitive programming):
```cpp
std::ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
std::cin.tie(nullptr);
```

**`std::ostringstream`** â€” in-memory string formatting (build strings with `<<`).
